{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14241"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.15,0.06,0.06,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96881"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"531"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12749"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45024"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96881"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old Aboriginal male presents to the Emergency Department in December with a three-day history of high fever, productive cough, and chest pain. He lives in a remote community in the Northern Territory and works as a gardener. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and bronchiectasis. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 29/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals crackles in the right lower zone. A chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the suspected diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sputum culture","Legionella urinary antigen test","Respiratory viral PCR","QuantiFERON-TB Gold test","Q fever serology"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s epidemiological and clinical risk factors, the most likely diagnosis in this case is melioidosis, caused by \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei.\u003C/em\u003E The most appropriate investigation to confirm this diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Esputum culture\u003C/strong\u003E. Sputum culture can directly identify the causative organism,\u003Cem\u003E B. pseudomallei,\u003C/em\u003E which is crucial for diagnosis and targeted treatment of melioidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeiloidosis results from infection with the soil and water bacterium \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei.\u003C/em\u003E The infection is endemic to northern Australia and parts of Southeast Asia. Diabetes is the most important risk factor for meiloidosis, followed by excess alcohol consumption, chronic kidney disease and chronic lung disease. Immunosuppressive therapy is also a significant risk factor. Around half of meiloidosis cases present with pneumonia, with other presentations ranging from skin lesions to sepsis with abscesses disseminated in multiple internal organs. Culture is the mainstay of diagnosis. Treatment of choice is usually ceftazidime or meropenem, subject to local guidelines and antibiotic resistance patterns.\u00a0Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in endemic areas are disproportionately affected by this disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003ELegionella\u003C/strong\u003E can cause atypical community-acquired pneumonia, it is less likely in this scenario given the patient\u0027s risk factors and geographical location. Legionella is usually associated with flu-like symptoms, muscle aches, tiredness and gastrointestinal problems, including nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea. Legionella can be found anywhere in water and soil across Australia, but is more often found in water systems such as cooling towers and spa pools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory viral PCR\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful to identify viral causes of pneumonia, such as influenza or SARS-CoV-2, although given the patient\u0027s epidemiological and clinical risk factors, meiloidosis is a more pertinent diagnosis to seek.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EQuantiFERON-TB Gold test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose latent tuberculosis infection. While TB can present with similar symptoms, the acute onset and geographical location make melioidosis a more likely diagnosis in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQ fever serology\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose Q fever, a zoonotic disease caused by \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii. \u003C/em\u003EWhile Q fever can cause pneumonia, it is more commonly associated with exposure to livestock, particularly cattle, sheep, and goats. The patient\u0027s occupation as a gardener and the geographical location make melioidosis a more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while all these tests have their place in diagnosing various causes of pneumonia, sputum culture is the most appropriate first-line investigation for this patient, given the high suspicion of melioidosis. It is important to note that melioidosis can be difficult to diagnose, and multiple specimens (blood, urine, sputum, throat swab) should be cultured to increase the likelihood of isolating \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Melioidosis is caused by the bacterium Burkholderia pseudomallei.","Melioidosis is endemic in northern Australia and can present with pneumonia, sepsis, or abscesses.","Diabetes is the most important risk factor for meiloidosis, followed by excess alcohol consumption, chronic kidney disease and chronic lung disease. Immunosuppressive therapy is also a significant risk factor.","Indigenous Australians are at higher risk of melioidosis due to increased exposure and higher rates of risk factors.","Culture is the mainstay of diagnosis of melioidosis, including sputum culture in patients presenting with respiratory symptoms and signs of infection."],"references":["Northern Territory Government. Melioidosis. In: Nt.gov.au [online]. 2024. Available at: https://health.nt.gov.au/public-health-notifiable-diseases/melioidosis","Australian Journal of General Practice. Melioidosis. In: RACGP [online]. 2022. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/may/melioidosis-an-updated-review"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T11:24:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T11:26:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6928"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","i